# NAME
. signals(7) - list of standard POSIX signals and their default actions

# SYNOPSIS
. signals(7)

# DESCRIPTION
. Signals are software interrupts sent to a process to notify it of
  specific events. When a signal is sent, the kernel interrupts the
  process's normal flow of execution to deliver the signal.

# SIGNAL DISPOSITION
. Each signal has a current **disposition**, which determines how the
  process behaves when it receives the signal.

- Term : Terminate the process.

- Ign  : Ignore the signal (discarded immediately).

- Core : Terminate the process and generate a core dump file.

- Stop : Stop (suspend) the process.

- Cont : Continue the process if it is currently stopped.

. A process can change the disposition of most signals using
  `sigaction(2)` or `signal(2)`. However, **SIGKILL** and **SIGSTOP**
  cannot be caught, blocked, or ignored.

# STANDARD SIGNALS
. Below are the most common standard signals.

| Signal | Value | Action | Description
| :--- | :--- | :--- | :---
| **SIGHUP** | 1 | Term | Hangup detected on controlling terminal.
| **SIGINT** | 2 | Term | Interrupt from keyboard (`Ctrl+C`).
| **SIGQUIT** | 3 | Core | Quit from keyboard (`Ctrl+\`).
| **SIGILL** | 4 | Core | Illegal Instruction.
| **SIGABRT** | 6 | Core | Abort signal from `abort(3)`.
| **SIGFPE** | 8 | Core | Floating-point exception.
| **SIGKILL** | 9 | Term | Kill signal (cannot be caught/ignored).
| **SIGSEGV** | 11 | Core | Segmentation fault (invalid memory ref).
| **SIGPIPE** | 13 | Term | Broken pipe: write to pipe with no readers.
| **SIGALRM** | 14 | Term | Timer signal from `alarm(2)`.
| **SIGTERM** | 15 | Term | Termination signal (request to exit).
| **SIGUSR1** | 10 | Term | User-defined signal 1.
| **SIGUSR2** | 12 | Term | User-defined signal 2.
| **SIGCHLD** | 17 | Ign | Child stopped or terminated.
| **SIGCONT** | 18 | Cont | Continue if stopped.
| **SIGSTOP** | 19 | Stop | Stop process (cannot be caught/ignored).
| **SIGTSTP** | 20 | Stop | Stop typed at terminal (`Ctrl+Z`).
| **SIGWINCH** | 28 | Ign | Window resize signal.

# ASYNC-SIGNAL-SAFETY
. A signal can interrupt a process at any point. If a signal handler
  calls a function that is partially through updating a global data
  structure, the system state may become inconsistent.

. Only **async-signal-safe** functions are guaranteed to be safe for
  use within a signal handler.

| Category | Safe Functions (Examples)
| :--- | :---
| I/O | `open`, `read`, `write`, `close`, `lseek`, `fstat`
| Process | `fork`, `execve`, `_exit`, `wait`, `waitpid`, `getpid`
| Signals | `sigaction`, `sigprocmask`, `sigpending`, `kill`, `raise`
| Memory | `memcpy`, `memmove`, `memset`, `strlen`
| Time | `time`, `clock_gettime`

# SIGNAL MASK & PENDING SIGNALS
. Each thread has a **signal mask**, a set of signals currently
  **blocked** from delivery.

. If a signal is generated while it is blocked, it becomes **pending**.
  It will remain pending until it is unblocked, at which point it will
  be delivered. Standard signals are not queued; if a blocked signal is
  generated multiple times, it is typically delivered only once when
  unblocked.

# SEE ALSO
. kill(1), ps(1), signal(2), sigaction(2), sigprocmask(2)
